SARS-CoV-2 viral infection can be divided into three stages: asymptomatic period, non-severe symptomatic period, and the severe infection stage. The infection symptoms appear after an incubation period of 5â€“6 days and the rapidity of symptoms appearence depends on patient's immune system and age (
 Skariyachan et al., 2019; 
 Hamid et al., 2020). The infected patients suffer usually from fever, dry cough, sore throat, myalgia, dyspnoea, tiredness, malaise among other less common symptoms including headache, abdominal pain, diarrhea, nausea, and vomiting (
 Song et al., 2020). This disease is mild in most young and healthy people. However, in cases of the elderly and those with comorbidities, and chronic diseases (hypertension, diabetes, respiratory system and cardiovascular diseases), it may progress to acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), pneumonia, acute renal and cardiac injuries and septic shock. Many people are asymptomatic and maybe just silent carriers of the virus (
 Liu et al., 2020; 
 Morley and Vellas, 2020; 
 Li and Xu, 2020).
